## 10. Weakest / Messiest Part of the Codebase

**`llm_client.py` + the LLM integration layer.**

This is the shakiest part of the entire system for several compounding reasons:

1. **No resilience.** When Gemini returns 429 (quota) or 503 (overloaded), the code catches the exception and returns a degraded fallback string like `"Recorded workflow (AI analysis failed)"`. It never retries, even though Google's error response literally includes a `retryDelay` field. This means any momentary rate limit silently degrades the user experience.

2. **Model selection is fragile.** The analysis model defaults to `gemini-pro-latest`, which on the free tier often has a quota of **zero** requests per minute. A user who just installed the app will immediately hit this wall on their first workflow recording (as you just experienced). It should default to `gemini-flash-latest`.

3. **Two separate LLM clients for the same API.** `llm_client.py` uses `langchain-google-genai` (`ChatGoogleGenerativeAI`), while `automation_runner.py` uses browser-use's own `ChatGoogle` (which wraps `google-genai`). These are two different Python SDKs talking to the same API with different auth flows, different error handling, and different model name formats. This split makes debugging and rate-limit management harder.

4. **The AVAILABLE_MODELS list is copy-pasted in 3 files** (`server.py`, `chat.py`, `settings.js`) with no single source of truth. When Google adds or deprecates models, all three must be updated manually.

**Runner-up:** The extension's `dashboard.js` at 1174 lines is a monolithic script with no modularity — UI rendering, API calls, IndexedDB queries, Mermaid rendering, drag-and-drop, chat logic, and modal management all live in one flat file.
